<div id=3D"what">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>What Is the Area of Ellipse?</h2>
</div>
<p data-speechify-sentence=3D"">Area of an ellipse is the <a href=3D"https:=
//www.cuemath.com/measurement/area/">area</a> or region covered by the <a h=
ref=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/geometry/ellipse/">ellipse</a> in two dimens=
ions. The area&nbsp;of an ellipse is expressed in square units like in<sup>=
2</sup>, cm<sup>2</sup>, m<sup>2</sup>, yd<sup>2</sup>, ft<sup>2</sup>, etc=
. Ellipse is a 2-D shape obtained by connecting all the points which are at=
 a constant distance from the two fixed points on the plane. The fixed poin=
ts are called <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/geometry/foci-of-ellipse/"=
>foci of ellipse</a>. F<sub>1</sub> and F<sub><font size=3D"1">2</font></su=
b>&nbsp;are the two foci.&nbsp;As an ellipse is not a perfect <a href=3D"ht=
tps://www.cuemath.com/geometry/circles/">circle</a>, the distance from the =
center of the ellipse to the points on the <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.c=
om/geometry/circumference-of-a-circle/">circumference</a>&nbsp;is not const=
ant. So, an ellipse has two radii.&nbsp;The longest chord in the ellipse&nb=
sp;is called the major axis of the ellipse.&nbsp;The minor axis is the chor=
d that is&nbsp;the <a href=3D"https://www.cuemath.com/geometry/perpendicula=
r-bisectors/">perpendicular bisector</a> to&nbsp;the major axis.</p>
<p data-speechify-sentence=3D""><img alt=3D"radii of an ellipse" src=3D"htt=
ps://d138zd1ktt9iqe.cloudfront.net/media/seo_landing_files/diksha-u-area-of=
-ellipse-01-1622084754.png" style=3D"max-width: 100%; width: 400px;"></p>
<p data-speechify-sentence=3D"">Ellipse is the&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.=
cuemath.com/geometry/locus/">locus</a> of all the points, whose <a href=3D"=
https://www.cuemath.com/numbers/sum/">sum</a> of distances&nbsp;from two fi=
xed points on a plane is constant.&nbsp;For example, in the images given be=
low the points P<sub>1</sub>, P<sub>2&nbsp;</sub>are located in such a way =
that&nbsp;the sum of the distances of point P<sub>1</sub>&nbsp;from the fix=
ed points F<sub>1&nbsp;</sub>and F<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;is equal to the&nbsp;su=
m of the distances of point P<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;from the fixed points&nbsp;F=
<sub>1&nbsp;</sub>and F<sub>2</sub>. That means if we join all such points&=
nbsp; P<sub>1</sub>, P<sub>2,&nbsp;</sub> P<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;, etc; we will=
 get a shape called an ellipse.</p>
<p data-speechify-sentence=3D"">&nbsp;</p>
